org.apache.ignite.streamer.index.tree

Class StreamerTreeIndexProvider<E,K,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.apache.ignite.streamer.index.StreamerIndexProviderAdapter<E,K,V>
      • org.apache.ignite.streamer.index.tree.StreamerTreeIndexProvider<E,K,V>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    StreamerIndexProvider<E,K,V>, StreamerIndexProviderMBean

    public class StreamerTreeIndexProvider<E,K,V>
extends StreamerIndexProviderAdapter<E,K,V>
    Tree index implementation of a StreamerIndexProvider.

    The advantage of a tree index is that it maintains entries in a sorted order, which is invaluable for many kinds of tasks, where event ordering makes sense (like GridStreamingPopularNumbersExample). The drawback is that the index entry values should be comparable to each other, and you'll are likely to need to implement a custom comparator for values in place of a default one.

    If ordering is not required, consider using StreamerHashIndexProvider instead, which is more efficient (O(1) vs. O(log(n))) and does not require comparability.

    See Also:
    StreamerHashIndexProvider
